WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.640 --> 00:00:07.310
KYLE EWING: My
name's Kyle Ewing.

00:00:07.310 --> 00:00:10.140
I lead the Global Staffing
Programs team here at Google.

00:00:10.140 --> 00:00:15.430
It's our job to identify and
develop top talent for Google.

00:00:15.430 --> 00:00:17.940
So when I was asked
to be here tonight--

00:00:17.940 --> 00:00:19.880
to sit here with these
guys and recognize

00:00:19.880 --> 00:00:24.120
Michael's story, a former BOLD
intern, I was very thrilled.

00:00:24.120 --> 00:00:27.100
I know we're all really
honored and excited to welcome

00:00:27.100 --> 00:00:31.740
Michael-- to welcome both
Jhanvi and Ketaki Shriram,

00:00:31.740 --> 00:00:34.361
the producers of the film, as
well as the director, Kevin

00:00:34.361 --> 00:00:34.860
Gordon.

00:00:34.860 --> 00:00:37.422
So please join me in giving
them a nice warm welcome.

00:00:37.422 --> 00:00:43.546
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:43.546 --> 00:00:45.670
So I think we all had the
pleasure of just watching

00:00:45.670 --> 00:00:46.060
the film.

00:00:46.060 --> 00:00:47.910
And those of us at
Google who've known you

00:00:47.910 --> 00:00:50.410
were so proud of Michael
and his accomplishments.

00:00:50.410 --> 00:00:54.040
But I'd love to hear more
about how you guys decided

00:00:54.040 --> 00:00:57.750
to feature Michael
and his story.

00:00:57.750 --> 00:01:00.395
KETAKI SHRIRAM: So Jhanvi and I
attended Stanford with Michael

00:01:00.395 --> 00:01:01.180
as undergrads.

00:01:01.180 --> 00:01:02.560
And when we heard he
was running for office

00:01:02.560 --> 00:01:04.110
we were very
inspired and excited.

00:01:04.110 --> 00:01:06.310
And so we met with
him over frozen yogurt

00:01:06.310 --> 00:01:08.700
and asked him if he'd be
OK with us following him

00:01:08.700 --> 00:01:10.834
on the campaign trail.

00:01:10.834 --> 00:01:11.750
KYLE EWING: Excellent.

00:01:11.750 --> 00:01:13.250
And what was your
reaction, Michael?

00:01:13.250 --> 00:01:16.295
MICHAEL TUBBS: At
first I was excited.

00:01:16.295 --> 00:01:17.170
But then I went home.

00:01:17.170 --> 00:01:18.880
I talked to my campaign manager.

00:01:18.880 --> 00:01:20.207
He said absolutely not.

00:01:20.207 --> 00:01:21.040
You're too reckless.

00:01:21.040 --> 00:01:23.206
They're going to catch you
in gotcha moments-- going

00:01:23.206 --> 00:01:24.940
to ruin the rest of your career.

00:01:24.940 --> 00:01:27.230
And then I remember
talking to my mom.

00:01:27.230 --> 00:01:29.920
And she said absolutely, for
you, I refuse to be on camera.

00:01:29.920 --> 00:01:31.180
I don't want them
asking me any questions.

00:01:31.180 --> 00:01:32.040
I don't want to be interviewed.

00:01:32.040 --> 00:01:33.970
And then if you
watch the movie it's,

00:01:33.970 --> 00:01:37.590
really about my campaign manager
and my mom, which is so ironic.

00:01:37.590 --> 00:01:39.574
They were so against it.

00:01:39.574 --> 00:01:41.990
KYLE EWING: I love how the
campaign manager at many points

00:01:41.990 --> 00:01:43.650
tried to mother you
too, throughout.

00:01:43.650 --> 00:01:44.858
MICHAEL TUBBS: He still does.

00:01:45.910 --> 00:01:47.410
KYLE EWING: Now,
Kevin, I understand

00:01:47.410 --> 00:01:49.970
this was your first
feature-length documentary.

00:01:49.970 --> 00:01:51.794
So how did you get
involved in the project?

00:01:51.794 --> 00:01:54.210
KEVIN GORDON: I knew Jhanvi
and Ketaki through film school

00:01:54.210 --> 00:01:55.070
at Stanford.

00:01:55.070 --> 00:01:57.640
And they reached out to me
about working on the project.

00:01:57.640 --> 00:01:59.790
And I had a background
in social justice work

00:01:59.790 --> 00:02:02.040
and been looking for something
that would reconnect me

00:02:02.040 --> 00:02:03.920
with that as well
my first project.

00:02:03.920 --> 00:02:05.709
And when I heard
about Michael I just

00:02:05.709 --> 00:02:08.250
knew it was going to be a good
fit and a really fun, exciting

00:02:08.250 --> 00:02:09.715
piece of history to document.

00:02:09.715 --> 00:02:11.340
KYLE EWING: And how
long from beginning

00:02:11.340 --> 00:02:13.720
to end-- as far as when you
guys decided to make the film

00:02:13.720 --> 00:02:15.410
and you had just
decided to run--

00:02:15.410 --> 00:02:17.040
how long was that process?

00:02:17.040 --> 00:02:18.280
JHANVI SHRIRAM: Almost
two and a half years.

00:02:18.280 --> 00:02:18.946
KYLE EWING: Wow.

00:02:18.946 --> 00:02:20.960
JHANVI SHRIRAM: We
started spring of 2012.

00:02:20.960 --> 00:02:24.110
And we just premiered at the
Tribeca Film Festival in April.

00:02:24.110 --> 00:02:26.190
So it was our first
public screening.

00:02:26.190 --> 00:02:28.488
So we're starting to take
it out more places now.

00:02:28.488 --> 00:02:29.196
KYLE EWING: Yeah.

00:02:29.196 --> 00:02:30.529
I was going to ask, what's next?

00:02:30.529 --> 00:02:32.460
I mean, Tribeca--
huge congratulations.

00:02:32.460 --> 00:02:33.310
That's a huge accomplishment.

00:02:33.310 --> 00:02:33.880
JHANVI SHRIRAM: Thank you.

00:02:33.880 --> 00:02:35.590
We are taking it out
to film festivals,

00:02:35.590 --> 00:02:37.260
doing special
screenings like this,

00:02:37.260 --> 00:02:39.560
taking it to
schools, nonprofits,

00:02:39.560 --> 00:02:41.320
and also seeking
distribution right now.

00:02:41.320 --> 00:02:43.950
So we don't have any
public knowledge yet.

00:02:43.950 --> 00:02:46.000
But hopefully soon
we'll be able to make it

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:49.634
to theaters or streaming
in other platforms.

00:02:49.634 --> 00:02:50.800
KYLE EWING: Huge to take on.

00:02:50.800 --> 00:02:53.300
I mean, the first
of a lot of things

00:02:53.300 --> 00:02:55.930
for all of you-- first
time to run, first time

00:02:55.930 --> 00:02:58.264
to produce to--
feature-length film.

00:02:58.264 --> 00:02:59.680
Where were you
guys when you heard

00:02:59.680 --> 00:03:02.290
that Tribeca had
invited you to premier?

00:03:02.290 --> 00:03:03.900
KETAKI SHRIRAM:
We actually all--

00:03:03.900 --> 00:03:06.390
we met up for
dinner in Palo Alto.

00:03:06.390 --> 00:03:09.266
And we brought cupcakes.

00:03:09.266 --> 00:03:10.140
Michael knows us now.

00:03:10.140 --> 00:03:11.670
Whenever we bring
dessert, it means

00:03:11.670 --> 00:03:13.600
something exciting's happened.

00:03:13.600 --> 00:03:16.610
And so that was kind of
how we broke the news.

00:03:16.610 --> 00:03:19.210
We were all very excited.

00:03:19.210 --> 00:03:20.720
KYLE EWING: Congratulations.

00:03:20.720 --> 00:03:24.049
Now Michael, you've become
an inspiration, I think,

00:03:24.049 --> 00:03:24.840
from the beginning.

00:03:24.840 --> 00:03:27.055
You've inspired youth
all over the place.

00:03:27.055 --> 00:03:28.680
And I'd love to hear
how you're dealing

00:03:28.680 --> 00:03:30.810
with your new-found
role model status.

00:03:30.810 --> 00:03:32.060
MICHAEL TUBBS: It's difficult.

00:03:32.060 --> 00:03:35.454
No, I think-- I've also
been incredibly blessed

00:03:35.454 --> 00:03:37.620
because the film does a
good job of showing just how

00:03:37.620 --> 00:03:39.400
humble my family
and friends are.

00:03:39.400 --> 00:03:41.560
So my inner circle,
they don't care

00:03:41.560 --> 00:03:44.580
whether Tribeca, or
Google Talk, or anything.

00:03:44.580 --> 00:03:47.530
Nothing's cool enough
for them anymore, anyway.

00:03:47.530 --> 00:03:49.540
So they really keep me
grounded and humble.

00:03:49.540 --> 00:03:50.040
OK.

00:03:50.040 --> 00:03:50.914
Don't get big-headed.

00:03:50.914 --> 00:03:51.560
OK.

00:03:51.560 --> 00:03:52.640
You just had homicide
on your street.

00:03:52.640 --> 00:03:53.300
What are you doing about that?

00:03:53.300 --> 00:03:53.540
OK.

00:03:53.540 --> 00:03:54.480
These kids still can't read.

00:03:54.480 --> 00:03:55.730
What are you doing about that?

00:03:55.730 --> 00:03:57.730
So I'm always pushed
to really focus on it.

00:03:57.730 --> 00:03:59.580
And I guess especially
because Stockton

00:03:59.580 --> 00:04:01.640
is an incredibly complex
place, none of these

00:04:01.640 --> 00:04:02.870
are easy things to solve.

00:04:02.870 --> 00:04:06.850
So it's kind of hard to be
too caught up in yourself

00:04:06.850 --> 00:04:10.020
when you have these issues
that are really difficult.

00:04:10.020 --> 00:04:12.895
But I also think that
being a role model,

00:04:12.895 --> 00:04:14.520
to answer your
question, because that's

00:04:14.520 --> 00:04:16.394
what you asked me about--
being a role model.

00:04:16.394 --> 00:04:18.730
I think in terms of
being a role model,

00:04:18.730 --> 00:04:21.120
I like it because it keeps
you really focused on trying

00:04:21.120 --> 00:04:23.300
to-- not being perfect--
I'm far from that.

00:04:23.300 --> 00:04:25.030
But trying to be my
best self every day.

00:04:25.030 --> 00:04:26.858
And then when I do mess
up or say something

00:04:26.858 --> 00:04:28.316
I shouldn't have
said in a meeting,

00:04:28.316 --> 00:04:32.604
I learned how to apologize
and model that as well.

00:04:32.604 --> 00:04:34.020
KYLE EWING: You
talked a lot and I

00:04:34.020 --> 00:04:36.150
knew you really demonstrated
how important it

00:04:36.150 --> 00:04:38.250
is to build a
coalition of people

00:04:38.250 --> 00:04:40.710
in the community to
really affect change.

00:04:40.710 --> 00:04:43.820
Can you tell us more about how
you define civic responsibility

00:04:43.820 --> 00:04:44.530
for yourself?

00:04:44.530 --> 00:04:46.030
MICHAEL TUBBS: It's
funny, actually,

00:04:46.030 --> 00:04:47.790
just to-- see I'm
not even answering

00:04:47.790 --> 00:04:49.451
your questions [INAUDIBLE].

00:04:49.451 --> 00:04:50.450
KYLE EWING: That's fine.

00:04:50.450 --> 00:04:51.600
Whatever works.

00:04:51.600 --> 00:04:53.266
MICHAEL TUBBS: I
wanted to say, in terms

00:04:53.266 --> 00:04:55.230
of the coalition-building,
I learned a lot of that

00:04:55.230 --> 00:04:56.360
actually as an intern
at Google, in terms

00:04:56.360 --> 00:04:57.859
of building a
cross-functional team.

00:04:57.859 --> 00:05:00.150
See, I got you.

00:05:00.150 --> 00:05:01.220
KYLE EWING: I like it.

00:05:01.220 --> 00:05:02.570
[APPLAUSE]

00:05:02.570 --> 00:05:05.960
KYLE EWING: But I think for me,
civic responsibility is number

00:05:05.960 --> 00:05:08.030
one, making the right
decisions as an elected,

00:05:08.030 --> 00:05:09.940
regardless of the
political consequences.

00:05:09.940 --> 00:05:13.370
But number two is also about
empowering the residents

00:05:13.370 --> 00:05:15.610
because Stockton
is 300,000 people.

00:05:15.610 --> 00:05:16.940
I represent 50,000 people.

00:05:16.940 --> 00:05:18.970
But it's a part-time job.

00:05:18.970 --> 00:05:20.574
I can't be everywhere
in the district.

00:05:20.574 --> 00:05:22.240
I don't live everywhere
in the district.

00:05:22.240 --> 00:05:24.260
I don't speak Spanish well.

00:05:24.260 --> 00:05:25.410
I don't speak Hmong well.

00:05:25.410 --> 00:05:26.660
I don't speak Vietnamese well.

00:05:26.660 --> 00:05:29.670
I don't speak all the different
languages in my district

00:05:29.670 --> 00:05:30.220
that well.

00:05:30.220 --> 00:05:32.660
So it's really about,
how do I engage everyone?

00:05:32.660 --> 00:05:35.981
How do I engage with the
huge-- substantial undocumented

00:05:35.981 --> 00:05:37.480
population in my
district so they're

00:05:37.480 --> 00:05:39.650
part of the
decision-making process?

00:05:39.650 --> 00:05:42.600
So in doing so, we've done
a lot of coalition-building

00:05:42.600 --> 00:05:46.510
around improving outcomes
for Boys and Men of Color

00:05:46.510 --> 00:05:49.910
around my district in terms
of our Reinvent South Stockton

00:05:49.910 --> 00:05:51.910
coalition around organizing
the black community.

00:05:51.910 --> 00:05:54.540
Because that's the only way in
our current political structure

00:05:54.540 --> 00:05:56.164
in Stockton that the
work can get done.

00:05:56.164 --> 00:05:57.820
Because I just can't
do it all myself

00:05:57.820 --> 00:05:58.528
KYLE EWING: Yeah.

00:05:58.528 --> 00:06:00.950
No, absolutely.

00:06:00.950 --> 00:06:02.620
You've also referenced
in the film--

00:06:02.620 --> 00:06:05.230
and since I've known
you and certainly read

00:06:05.230 --> 00:06:07.660
a lot of great things about
you-- how Martin Luther

00:06:07.660 --> 00:06:08.912
King really inspired you.

00:06:08.912 --> 00:06:11.120
I'd love to hear more about
the civil rights movement

00:06:11.120 --> 00:06:13.860
and how that's really influenced
your leadership style.

00:06:13.860 --> 00:06:14.690
MICHAEL TUBBS: This is
going to be a long answer

00:06:14.690 --> 00:06:16.295
but I think there's
a couple things.

00:06:16.295 --> 00:06:18.420
My junior year-- junior
year was such a great year.

00:06:18.420 --> 00:06:19.725
So I interned at Google.

00:06:19.725 --> 00:06:21.264
Then I went to the White House.

00:06:21.264 --> 00:06:22.430
Then I partied in Cape Town.

00:06:22.430 --> 00:06:24.840
And then when I got back, I got
to reenact these freedom rides

00:06:24.840 --> 00:06:26.214
with the original
freedom riders.

00:06:26.214 --> 00:06:28.830
So I spent 10 days with the
original freedom riders.

00:06:28.830 --> 00:06:31.500
And we went from
DC to New Orleans.

00:06:31.500 --> 00:06:34.240
So we went to
Montgomery, Alabama,

00:06:34.240 --> 00:06:36.130
where people beaten
in Montgomery

00:06:36.130 --> 00:06:39.580
that-- it was just a really
very powerful and special time.

00:06:39.580 --> 00:06:40.730
From them, I learned a lot.

00:06:40.730 --> 00:06:42.480
the first thing was
that they were all 19,

00:06:42.480 --> 00:06:45.310
20, 21, 22-years-old when
they were on this bus.

00:06:45.310 --> 00:06:47.170
And Doctor King was
26 when he started,

00:06:47.170 --> 00:06:49.030
when he led the bus
boycott in Montgomery.

00:06:49.030 --> 00:06:50.390
So they were all really young.

00:06:50.390 --> 00:06:51.473
And they would say things.

00:06:51.473 --> 00:06:54.140
And there was one conversation
in particular-- a man,

00:06:54.140 --> 00:06:55.310
Bob Singleton.

00:06:55.310 --> 00:06:56.990
He's a professor at LMU now.

00:06:56.990 --> 00:06:58.520
We brought him out to Stockton
for Black History Month.

00:06:58.520 --> 00:06:59.978
And we were on the
back of the bus.

00:06:59.978 --> 00:07:01.175
And we were cracking jokes.

00:07:01.175 --> 00:07:02.630
And he was just staring at me.

00:07:02.630 --> 00:07:04.909
So I'm staring back
at him, like OK.

00:07:04.909 --> 00:07:05.450
I'll be good.

00:07:05.450 --> 00:07:06.110
I'll be quiet.

00:07:06.110 --> 00:07:07.959
And then he says, young man.

00:07:07.959 --> 00:07:08.750
And I say, yes sir.

00:07:08.750 --> 00:07:13.386
And he said, I was
arrested on August 4, 1961.

00:07:13.386 --> 00:07:14.640
I said, OK.

00:07:14.640 --> 00:07:17.700
And then he said, why
is that day important?

00:07:17.700 --> 00:07:19.851
And I said, because
you were arrested.

00:07:19.851 --> 00:07:21.350
And that's important
for my freedom.

00:07:21.350 --> 00:07:23.720
I would not be on this bus if
you weren't arrested that day.

00:07:23.720 --> 00:07:24.225
I heard you I was listening.

00:07:24.225 --> 00:07:25.120
And then he laughed.

00:07:25.120 --> 00:07:28.380
And then he said, on that
day, Barack Obama was born.

00:07:28.380 --> 00:07:30.040
And then he said,
I was 19-years-old.

00:07:30.040 --> 00:07:32.380
I had no idea that the
decision I made at 19

00:07:32.380 --> 00:07:34.610
would pave the way 50
years later for a kid who

00:07:34.610 --> 00:07:37.090
couldn't get a cup of
coffee to become president.

00:07:37.090 --> 00:07:38.840
And then he said, what
are you doing today

00:07:38.840 --> 00:07:40.980
so that 50 years from
now a kid in Stockton

00:07:40.980 --> 00:07:42.642
has every opportunity you had?

00:07:42.642 --> 00:07:44.100
And I was 20-years-old
at the time.

00:07:44.100 --> 00:07:46.490
I was trying to figure out
life and what I wanted to do.

00:07:46.490 --> 00:07:47.930
And that really stuck with me.

00:07:47.930 --> 00:07:49.810
And then one of
my biggest mentors

00:07:49.810 --> 00:07:50.852
is Marian Wright Edelman.

00:07:50.852 --> 00:07:52.935
And she's the head of
[? the Children's ?] Defense

00:07:52.935 --> 00:07:53.690
Fund.

00:07:53.690 --> 00:07:55.130
She marched with Doctor King.

00:07:55.130 --> 00:07:57.240
She was a-- first
African American woman

00:07:57.240 --> 00:07:58.915
admitted to the
Mississippi state bar.

00:07:58.915 --> 00:08:00.290
She practiced law
in Mississippi.

00:08:00.290 --> 00:08:02.710
This huge civil rights
advocate that's been

00:08:02.710 --> 00:08:06.040
active for the past 50 years
doing social justice work.

00:08:06.040 --> 00:08:08.272
And I was able to be
[INAUDIBLE] programs

00:08:08.272 --> 00:08:09.230
all throughout college.

00:08:09.230 --> 00:08:12.190
So I would get these
nuggets of wisdom from her.

00:08:12.190 --> 00:08:14.320
And the biggest one
she said was that it's

00:08:14.320 --> 00:08:16.310
a privilege to
struggle for justice.

00:08:16.310 --> 00:08:19.210
And I said, huh?

00:08:19.210 --> 00:08:20.835
She said, it's a
privilege to struggle.

00:08:20.835 --> 00:08:23.335
And she said, because you come
from a long line of struggle.

00:08:23.335 --> 00:08:25.560
And she brought it back
from Harriet Tubman, who

00:08:25.560 --> 00:08:27.100
couldn't read but
somehow knew how

00:08:27.100 --> 00:08:29.620
to read the stars and outsmarted
everyone and freed people.

00:08:29.620 --> 00:08:31.460
She just went down
throughout history.

00:08:31.460 --> 00:08:34.246
And then she said, justice
work is like a baton.

00:08:34.246 --> 00:08:35.870
It's a privilege to
be given the mantle

00:08:35.870 --> 00:08:37.530
to keep the work forward.

00:08:37.530 --> 00:08:39.954
So I've just learned a
lot from the civil rights

00:08:39.954 --> 00:08:41.870
movement people in terms
of what I've studied.

00:08:41.870 --> 00:08:44.286
But also those I've been able
to have a relationship with.

00:08:44.286 --> 00:08:45.170
KYLE EWING: Yeah.

00:08:45.170 --> 00:08:48.030
Well speaking of
influence, Kevin,

00:08:48.030 --> 00:08:50.500
I'd love to hear-- I've heard
that directors will have

00:08:50.500 --> 00:08:52.715
a vision when they
embark on a project.

00:08:52.715 --> 00:08:55.090
And then when it's all said
and done for better or worse,

00:08:55.090 --> 00:08:56.423
that vision has sort of shifted.

00:08:56.423 --> 00:08:57.810
And it's played out differently.

00:08:57.810 --> 00:09:00.200
Was there anything that's
different about the narrative

00:09:00.200 --> 00:09:03.430
that we saw than what you
thought it might look like?

00:09:03.430 --> 00:09:04.680
KEVIN GORDON: Yeah definitely.

00:09:04.680 --> 00:09:07.950
I'd say stylistically,
I wanted the film

00:09:07.950 --> 00:09:10.272
to fit into this long
tradition of political campaign

00:09:10.272 --> 00:09:12.480
documentaries which are all
kind of that run-and-gun,

00:09:12.480 --> 00:09:15.260
chasing the candidate
kind of look.

00:09:15.260 --> 00:09:17.760
But as far as what we thought
the storyline was going to be,

00:09:17.760 --> 00:09:19.110
we definitely
thought the opponent

00:09:19.110 --> 00:09:20.901
was going to be a bigger
part of the story.

00:09:20.901 --> 00:09:23.280
And he turned out not to be.

00:09:23.280 --> 00:09:27.220
And the bigger challenge
was the problems

00:09:27.220 --> 00:09:30.010
facing the city as well as
Michael's own transformation

00:09:30.010 --> 00:09:32.280
over the course of the campaign.

00:09:32.280 --> 00:09:34.590
And the other big surprise
was the campaign manager

00:09:34.590 --> 00:09:37.920
because Nick, first
day when we were there,

00:09:37.920 --> 00:09:39.670
he didn't even want
me to film the meeting

00:09:39.670 --> 00:09:40.795
he was having with Michael.

00:09:40.795 --> 00:09:42.690
He was like, oh, no,
it's too high level.

00:09:42.690 --> 00:09:45.689
And then by the end he was
like, OK you can film just this.

00:09:45.689 --> 00:09:47.730
And then it just kept
growing until he completely

00:09:47.730 --> 00:09:50.150
opened up to us about
his entire life.

00:09:50.150 --> 00:09:52.520
And I'd say his back
story and his motivation

00:09:52.520 --> 00:09:54.970
was the biggest
surprise in the film.

00:09:54.970 --> 00:09:56.870
And then Michael's
mom-- as Michael said,

00:09:56.870 --> 00:09:58.160
she wasn't on board at first.

00:09:58.160 --> 00:10:00.800
And she had this
really amazing ability

00:10:00.800 --> 00:10:02.300
to sense when the
camera was on her,

00:10:02.300 --> 00:10:04.320
even if I was on the
other side of the room.

00:10:04.320 --> 00:10:05.780
She would just turn around.

00:10:05.780 --> 00:10:07.500
I was like OK, OK, don't film.

00:10:07.500 --> 00:10:13.270
But she gave us just enough
to have this tremendous arc

00:10:13.270 --> 00:10:15.166
that I think's a beautiful
part of the film.

00:10:15.166 --> 00:10:15.874
KYLE EWING: Yeah.

00:10:15.874 --> 00:10:16.420
Yeah.

00:10:16.420 --> 00:10:19.585
Can you guys tell us
about the title, True Son?

00:10:19.585 --> 00:10:20.460
KETAKI SHRIRAM: Yeah.

00:10:20.460 --> 00:10:24.460
We read about Michael being the
true son returning to Stockton.

00:10:24.460 --> 00:10:27.000
