00:13:56.776 --> 00:13:59.304
to make your way into
the political sphere,

00:13:59.304 --> 00:14:00.970
and trying to get
your foot in the door.

00:14:00.970 --> 00:14:02.770
And I was wondering
what advice could you

00:14:02.770 --> 00:14:07.890
give to aspiring civic
advocates or politicians

00:14:07.890 --> 00:14:11.942
to be elected one day
in their community?

00:14:11.942 --> 00:14:12.858
MICHAEL TUBBS: Man.

00:14:12.858 --> 00:14:14.480
I forgot Google
people are smart.

00:14:14.480 --> 00:14:16.280
So you guys are asking
smart questions.

00:14:16.280 --> 00:14:17.475
[LAUGHTER]

00:14:17.475 --> 00:14:19.100
MICHAEL TUBBS: I
think a couple things.

00:14:19.100 --> 00:14:22.310
I think number one, it
has to be more than just

00:14:22.310 --> 00:14:23.640
about an office or a position.

00:14:23.640 --> 00:14:26.200
There has to be an issue or some
policy that really motivates

00:14:26.200 --> 00:14:29.650
you because no one
likes politicians.

00:14:29.650 --> 00:14:31.060
I don't like politicians.

00:14:31.060 --> 00:14:32.520
if you're really
just a politician,

00:14:32.520 --> 00:14:34.920
you're not my friend
[INAUDIBLE] to work with you.

00:14:34.920 --> 00:14:37.830
The second thing I would
say is just be authentic.

00:14:37.830 --> 00:14:40.000
I think oftentimes,
people think they

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:41.455
need to fit into
some sort of mold

00:14:41.455 --> 00:14:42.955
of what it means
to be a politician.

00:14:42.955 --> 00:14:44.930
But especially at a
really local level,

00:14:44.930 --> 00:14:46.400
people value authenticity.

00:14:46.400 --> 00:14:48.795
They value people who
can speak the truth, who

00:14:48.795 --> 00:14:50.750
can say they don't know
when they don't know,

00:14:50.750 --> 00:14:52.666
who will say they want
a mimosa at brunch when

00:14:52.666 --> 00:14:54.400
they're at brunch with mimosas.

00:14:54.400 --> 00:14:56.340
People value that.

00:14:56.340 --> 00:14:58.861
I think number three--
and what I realized

00:14:58.861 --> 00:15:00.360
and I think the
film does a good job

00:15:00.360 --> 00:15:03.050
showing it-- is that the
relationships I built before I

00:15:03.050 --> 00:15:05.130
knew I was running for
office were so helpful.

00:15:05.130 --> 00:15:07.440
All the people that walked
and knocked on doors for me

00:15:07.440 --> 00:15:09.474
were people I met, and
I was in high school,

00:15:09.474 --> 00:15:11.890
and I helped tutor them, or
they were kids I had mentored,

00:15:11.890 --> 00:15:14.250
or they were people
I had gone out with

00:15:14.250 --> 00:15:15.420
and we had a good time.

00:15:15.420 --> 00:15:19.407
So I think it's about really
caring about relationships

00:15:19.407 --> 00:15:20.240
in the here and now.

00:15:20.240 --> 00:15:21.510
And then number four,
I think it's also

00:15:21.510 --> 00:15:22.885
about building
some sort of skill

00:15:22.885 --> 00:15:24.510
set in terms of what can you do?

00:15:24.510 --> 00:15:25.390
What have you done?

00:15:25.390 --> 00:15:27.780
Because oftentimes
people look at past--

00:15:27.780 --> 00:15:29.330
it's just like
looking for a job.

00:15:29.330 --> 00:15:30.746
People look at
past success-- even

00:15:30.746 --> 00:15:34.180
if it's on a smaller scale--
to illustrate future progress.

00:15:34.180 --> 00:15:36.660
And I would say on
the skills I learned,

00:15:36.660 --> 00:15:38.530
whether running my own
nonprofit in college,

00:15:38.530 --> 00:15:40.821
or running my own summer
leadership program in college,

00:15:40.821 --> 00:15:44.190
or working at Google,
on the smaller scale,

00:15:44.190 --> 00:15:47.190
it's still the same skills
I use now as a politician.

00:15:47.190 --> 00:15:48.750
And the last point
I would say is

00:15:48.750 --> 00:15:50.340
get really good at
working with people

00:15:50.340 --> 00:15:52.740
because-- I'm going to
tell you a funny story

00:15:52.740 --> 00:15:54.984
and then I'm going
to stop talking.

00:15:54.984 --> 00:15:57.400
Before I came here I was in a
meeting around a health care

00:15:57.400 --> 00:16:00.550
clinic in my district with
two ultra-conservative, older

00:16:00.550 --> 00:16:01.850
white men who, I love.

00:16:01.850 --> 00:16:03.380
So they invite me in.

00:16:03.380 --> 00:16:05.664
And then he gives me this
pen to take notes with.

00:16:05.664 --> 00:16:06.455
It says The Factor.

00:16:06.455 --> 00:16:08.010
And I'm like, this
a really good pen.

00:16:08.010 --> 00:16:08.770
So I was going to
try to take it.

00:16:08.770 --> 00:16:10.478
But I didn't want to
feed the stereotype.

00:16:10.478 --> 00:16:13.240
So I say-- so I gave
him his pen back.

00:16:13.240 --> 00:16:14.920
And he said, no
you could keep it.

00:16:14.920 --> 00:16:17.970
It's my premium member
O'Reilly Factor pen.

00:16:17.970 --> 00:16:19.550
I just look at him.

00:16:19.550 --> 00:16:21.035
I don't like O'Reilly that much.

00:16:21.035 --> 00:16:22.310
[LAUGHTER]

00:16:22.310 --> 00:16:24.570
MICHAEL TUBBS: So I look
at him, whatever, it works.

00:16:24.570 --> 00:16:27.550
And then he started-- and then
they both huddled in and were

00:16:27.550 --> 00:16:30.400
like, "we're
ultra-conservatives."

00:16:30.400 --> 00:16:31.832
And then I say,
oh I forgive you.

00:16:31.832 --> 00:16:33.040
And we just started laughing.

00:16:33.040 --> 00:16:34.540
And I say, I'm going
to write really

00:16:34.540 --> 00:16:38.270
progressive legislation with
your O'Reilly Factor pen.

00:16:38.270 --> 00:16:39.850
I share that story
just to illustrate

00:16:39.850 --> 00:16:43.072
that oftentimes labels operate
as silos to stop people

00:16:43.072 --> 00:16:44.280
from working with each other.

00:16:44.280 --> 00:16:47.162
Because although we probably
don't agree on a lot of things,

00:16:47.162 --> 00:16:48.620
we agree that people
in my district

00:16:48.620 --> 00:16:49.661
need health care clinics.

00:16:49.661 --> 00:16:52.231
And I'm glad I didn't let their
labels as ultra-conservative

00:16:52.231 --> 00:16:54.730
stop me from spending an hour
and a half with them designing

00:16:54.730 --> 00:16:55.396
a health clinic.

00:16:55.396 --> 00:16:57.230
Because it's important.

00:16:57.230 --> 00:16:58.970
I'm not sure what the
point was of that.

00:16:58.970 --> 00:17:00.237
But yeah, that's my advice.

00:17:00.237 --> 00:17:00.736
[LAUGHTER]

