00:18:22.690 --> 00:18:26.300
is very good with
mathematics, engineering,

00:18:26.300 --> 00:18:31.381
whatever-- what can I bring
to a campaign like this?

00:18:31.381 --> 00:18:32.880
MICHAEL TUBBS: My
man, are you open?

00:18:32.880 --> 00:18:33.380
Are you--

00:18:33.380 --> 00:18:37.990
[LAUGHTER]

00:18:37.990 --> 00:18:38.740
AUDIENCE: Well no.

00:18:38.740 --> 00:18:40.430
I mean I'm an intern,
but thank you.

00:18:40.430 --> 00:18:45.490
MICHAEL TUBBS: I think I'mma
talk a lot so [INAUDIBLE].

00:18:45.490 --> 00:18:47.156
KEVIN GORDON: There's
definitely a place

00:18:47.156 --> 00:18:48.990
for technology in campaigns.

00:18:48.990 --> 00:18:51.060
Actually, at one point
Michael and his campaign

00:18:51.060 --> 00:18:54.024
tried to be innovative
and have the first-- what

00:18:54.024 --> 00:18:54.690
did you call it?

00:18:54.690 --> 00:18:56.356
MICHAEL TUBBS: Google
Hangout Town Hall.

00:18:56.356 --> 00:18:56.980
[LAUGHTER]

00:18:56.980 --> 00:18:59.480
KEVIN GORDON: It was a Town
hall via Google Hangout, which--

00:18:59.480 --> 00:19:00.855
MICHAEL TUBBS: It
was a disaster.

00:19:00.855 --> 00:19:01.680
But we tried.

00:19:01.680 --> 00:19:02.940
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:19:02.940 --> 00:19:04.360
KEVIN GORDON: That was
actually the saddest thing

00:19:04.360 --> 00:19:06.401
for me was that that didn't
make it in the movie.

00:19:06.401 --> 00:19:07.610
Because that was hilarious.

00:19:07.610 --> 00:19:09.190
So I think there's
definitely some improvements

00:19:09.190 --> 00:19:10.190
that we could have made.

00:19:10.190 --> 00:19:11.981
JHANVI SHRIRAM: Google
Hangouts is awesome.

00:19:11.981 --> 00:19:13.565
We used it a lot to
plan for the film.

00:19:13.565 --> 00:19:15.230
Because we were all
in different places.

00:19:15.230 --> 00:19:16.770
So it was successful
in some parts

00:19:16.770 --> 00:19:17.937
of the film of the campaign.

00:19:17.937 --> 00:19:19.311
KEVIN GORDON: I
just met somebody

00:19:19.311 --> 00:19:20.980
who's got an app
called Organizer.

00:19:20.980 --> 00:19:23.970
And they are turning everything
that Michael and his campaign

00:19:23.970 --> 00:19:25.840
were doing into an app
that's unbelievable.

00:19:25.840 --> 00:19:28.402
One of the biggest things was
they have walk lists, which--

00:19:28.402 --> 00:19:30.360
Michael's campaign they
weren't even using them

00:19:30.360 --> 00:19:31.276
when we first started.

00:19:31.276 --> 00:19:32.932
But then there was
always a disaster

00:19:32.932 --> 00:19:35.390
or often there was a disaster
because they were misprinted.

00:19:35.390 --> 00:19:37.680
And it has the name of the
person you're talking to,

00:19:37.680 --> 00:19:39.824
their address, their
previous voting history.

00:19:39.824 --> 00:19:41.240
But now there's
an app that has it

00:19:41.240 --> 00:19:43.761
all just on a phone
along with the script

00:19:43.761 --> 00:19:45.010
right there for people to use.

00:19:45.010 --> 00:19:49.027
So that really--
revolutionizing campaign work.

00:19:49.027 --> 00:19:50.110
MICHAEL TUBBS: Absolutely.

00:19:50.110 --> 00:19:52.010
Technology-- I
wish-- I was going

00:19:52.010 --> 00:19:53.780
to try to get someone to teach
me how to code before here.

00:19:53.780 --> 00:19:54.800
But I got here a
little bit too late.

00:19:54.800 --> 00:19:56.200
I wish I had that skill set.

00:19:56.200 --> 00:19:57.707
Because I feel
like a lot of stuff

00:19:57.707 --> 00:19:59.540
I do could be a lot
more efficient if I just

00:19:59.540 --> 00:20:01.217
knew the computer-y stuff to do.

00:20:01.217 --> 00:20:02.675
So to your question,
I really think

00:20:02.675 --> 00:20:04.466
there's a lot of things
with building apps,

00:20:04.466 --> 00:20:07.122
with helping people use data
and analytics more effectively,

00:20:07.122 --> 00:20:09.080
in terms of helping people
with their websites.

00:20:09.080 --> 00:20:11.615
A lot of political websites
aren't really functional.

00:20:11.615 --> 00:20:12.448
AUDIENCE: Oh my god.

00:20:12.448 --> 00:20:13.010
It's so bad.

00:20:13.010 --> 00:20:13.829
MICHAEL TUBBS: Man.

00:20:13.829 --> 00:20:14.620
AUDIENCE: Big ones.

00:20:14.620 --> 00:20:17.062
MICHAEL TUBBS: But my
website's high tech.

00:20:17.062 --> 00:20:18.312
Everyone's not feeling it.

00:20:21.310 --> 00:20:23.310
There's a whole, probably,
consultancy out there

00:20:23.310 --> 00:20:27.190
of people who need really smart,
techie people to help them make

00:20:27.190 --> 00:20:30.086
their campaign into
the 21st century.

00:20:30.086 --> 00:20:32.100
That could be your tag
line, making campaigns

00:20:32.100 --> 00:20:35.117
into the 21st century.

00:20:35.117 --> 00:20:35.950
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:20:38.950 --> 00:20:41.320
KYLE EWING: Anyone else?

00:20:41.320 --> 00:20:42.620
The former manager--

00:20:42.620 --> 00:20:43.495
MICHAEL TUBBS: Uh oh.

00:20:46.440 --> 00:20:49.130
AUDIENCE: So Michael, you
could have done anything.

00:20:49.130 --> 00:20:53.150
You've got such a passion
to affect change and also

00:20:53.150 --> 00:20:55.370
this ability to
connect with people.

00:20:55.370 --> 00:20:58.540
So what is it-- you could have
affected change in Stockton

00:20:58.540 --> 00:21:00.900
in so many ways.

00:21:00.900 --> 00:21:04.100
Tell us a little
bit about why run?

00:21:04.100 --> 00:21:06.807
And why is this your
mechanism right now?

00:21:06.807 --> 00:21:09.140
MICHAEL TUBBS: That's another
long-- I'm sorry you guys.

00:21:09.140 --> 00:21:10.931
I don't really talk
this long all the time.

00:21:10.931 --> 00:21:13.350
But these are very
thorough questions.

00:21:13.350 --> 00:21:14.730
I think it was a couple things.

00:21:14.730 --> 00:21:17.816
So my senior year I was
applying for things.

00:21:17.816 --> 00:21:19.190
And after my cousin
was murdered,

00:21:19.190 --> 00:21:20.620
I said I was going back
to Stockton one day.

00:21:20.620 --> 00:21:22.890
But it was going to be in,
like, 2020 because I wanted

00:21:22.890 --> 00:21:24.390
to make some money
like my mom said.

00:21:24.390 --> 00:21:26.130
That was our secret plan.

00:21:26.130 --> 00:21:28.660
Or not-so secret plan.

00:21:28.660 --> 00:21:31.340
But then I was really
trying to think about,

00:21:31.340 --> 00:21:33.800
what's the biggest way
to make an impact now?

00:21:33.800 --> 00:21:37.410
And I figured interning
for someone or work

00:21:37.410 --> 00:21:39.870
being as someone's staffer
could make an impact.

00:21:39.870 --> 00:21:42.540
But being on City
Council, even if I lost,

00:21:42.540 --> 00:21:45.510
is changing the narrative and
the course of the campaign--

00:21:45.510 --> 00:21:46.580
would make a real change.

00:21:46.580 --> 00:21:49.984
And I still could apply for
jobs and stuff afterwards.

00:21:49.984 --> 00:21:51.900
So I think that for me,
that was the question.

00:21:51.900 --> 00:21:53.920
Where can I make the
most impact right

00:21:53.920 --> 00:21:56.320
now-- a 21-year-old
with no real experience?

00:21:56.320 --> 00:21:59.812
And well, campaigns are really--
that's a real meritocracy.

00:21:59.812 --> 00:22:01.020
You just have to get elected.

00:22:01.020 --> 00:22:01.980
You don't really need
to know anything.

00:22:01.980 --> 00:22:04.890
If you get 51% of the vote,
you're now making decisions.

00:22:04.890 --> 00:22:06.629
So I thought, at
21-years-old that

00:22:06.629 --> 00:22:08.920
was the biggest way I could
make an impact on the city.

00:22:08.920 --> 00:22:11.420
Especially because
when I ran we had just

00:22:11.420 --> 00:22:13.750
gotten to two years
of record homicide.

00:22:13.750 --> 00:22:15.230
We had just declared bankruptcy.

00:22:15.230 --> 00:22:17.224
It was really not
the place to be.

00:22:17.224 --> 00:22:18.140
So I said, oh my gosh.

00:22:18.140 --> 00:22:19.640
This would be-- I'm kind
of weird like this--

00:22:19.640 --> 00:22:20.050
I was like, oh my gosh.

00:22:20.050 --> 00:22:22.950
It would be a great opportunity
to affectualize some change.

00:22:22.950 --> 00:22:25.130
But I'm not
convinced that's what

00:22:25.130 --> 00:22:26.777
it's going to be
for me long-term.

00:22:26.777 --> 00:22:28.985
I think at some point I want
to do some philanthropy.

00:22:28.985 --> 00:22:31.600
Because I spend all my time
calling foundations and saying,

00:22:31.600 --> 00:22:33.080
I need you to invest in this.

00:22:33.080 --> 00:22:35.640
So I think there's a
role for philanthropy.

00:22:35.640 --> 00:22:37.690
Also, I teach too, full-time.

00:22:37.690 --> 00:22:39.885
So I think at some point
I want to open a school

00:22:39.885 --> 00:22:41.150
or be a superintendent.

00:22:41.150 --> 00:22:43.810
So I'm really just keeping
myself really open in terms

00:22:43.810 --> 00:22:45.970
of where can I make
the most impact.

00:22:45.970 --> 00:22:48.555
But I do think
through 2016, being

00:22:48.555 --> 00:22:51.650
on City Council is probably
the biggest way to do that.

00:22:51.650 --> 00:22:53.150
KYLE EWING: I have
a quick follow up

00:22:53.150 --> 00:22:54.590
and then we'll hand it to you.

00:22:54.590 --> 00:22:56.279
Quickly, on that, you
talk about impact.

00:22:56.279 --> 00:22:58.570
And one of the things that
really struck me in the film

00:22:58.570 --> 00:23:00.740
is you talk about
your life experiences,

00:23:00.740 --> 00:23:03.590
to this point, really
teaching you to be optimistic,

00:23:03.590 --> 00:23:06.440
and that things that
start out bad most of time

00:23:06.440 --> 00:23:08.062
turn out good eventually.

00:23:08.062 --> 00:23:10.020
You've just mentioned
Stockton's homicide rate.

00:23:10.020 --> 00:23:12.920
It's down like 60%
since you've been in.

00:23:15.744 --> 00:23:17.493
MICHAEL TUBBS: I wish
I could take credit.

00:23:17.493 --> 00:23:18.762
I just came down
from Mount Sinai

00:23:18.762 --> 00:23:19.610
with the ten commandments.

00:23:19.610 --> 00:23:21.610
KYLE EWING: But what do
you attribute the change

00:23:21.610 --> 00:23:22.607
to-- the decrease?

00:23:22.607 --> 00:23:24.440
MICHAEL TUBBS: I do
have a small part in it.

00:23:24.440 --> 00:23:25.690
And I will take a
little bit in that.

00:23:25.690 --> 00:23:26.790
KYLE EWING: Take it.

00:23:26.790 --> 00:23:29.270
MICHAEL TUBBS: I think that
number one, the community

00:23:29.270 --> 00:23:31.250
got really serious
about the crime problem.

00:23:31.250 --> 00:23:33.500
So we brought this thing
called Operation Ceasefire,

00:23:33.500 --> 00:23:36.100
which is like the number
one, evidence-based,

00:23:36.100 --> 00:23:38.210
not experience-based, not
just how-I-feel-based,

00:23:38.210 --> 00:23:40.650
but evidence-- there's
research that shows it works--

00:23:40.650 --> 00:23:41.340
based program.

00:23:41.340 --> 00:23:43.379
And we had it
about a decade ago.

00:23:43.379 --> 00:23:44.170
And it was working.

00:23:44.170 --> 00:23:46.500
And then after we
got homicides down.

00:23:46.500 --> 00:23:47.042
We let it go.

00:23:47.042 --> 00:23:48.583
So this time we're
really-- I've been

00:23:48.583 --> 00:23:50.120
adamant about
institutionalizing it.

00:23:50.120 --> 00:23:51.760
So that's been really helpful.

00:23:51.760 --> 00:23:53.929
And then this summer
we're opening this Office

00:23:53.929 --> 00:23:56.470
of Violence Prevention that I've
worked close with the police

00:23:56.470 --> 00:23:59.750
chief in designing to figure
out how to become the nation's

00:23:59.750 --> 00:24:03.570
leader in evidence-based
violence prevention programs.

00:24:03.570 --> 00:24:06.647
And we've also really
widened our thinking past,

00:24:06.647 --> 00:24:08.550
we need to
incarcerate everybody.

00:24:08.550 --> 00:24:09.590
We're just going to
throw them in jail

00:24:09.590 --> 00:24:10.730
and that's going to
solve their problem.

00:24:10.730 --> 00:24:12.410
But really look at some
of the root causes.

00:24:12.410 --> 00:24:13.480
What's going on in the schools?

00:24:13.480 --> 00:24:14.813
What's going on in the families?

00:24:14.813 --> 00:24:17.454
And then using data
to predict things.

00:24:17.454 --> 00:24:19.370
It's almost like people
analytics in terms of,

00:24:19.370 --> 00:24:21.920
what are some of the triggers
that make someone likely to be

00:24:21.920 --> 00:24:23.780
a victim or approached
for a crime?

00:24:23.780 --> 00:24:26.224
And since we have
that data, we use it.

00:24:26.224 --> 00:24:27.640
And I'm a nervous
so this is going

00:24:27.640 --> 00:24:31.240
to be my quick [INAUDIBLE]
though we found out that of all

00:24:31.240 --> 00:24:32.760
the homicide
victims and suspects

00:24:32.760 --> 00:24:35.844
in Stockton, most of them
had been arrested six times

00:24:35.844 --> 00:24:37.260
and were on
probation, or just off

00:24:37.260 --> 00:24:39.060
probation, which means
we knew who they were.

00:24:39.060 --> 00:24:40.070
We have contact with them.

00:24:40.070 --> 00:24:41.680
And we have leverage
to bring them in.

00:24:41.680 --> 00:24:43.850
So we finally used that
data to call them in

00:24:43.850 --> 00:24:45.249
and say, hey we
know who you are.

00:24:45.249 --> 00:24:47.040
We know what groups
you're affiliated with.

00:24:47.040 --> 00:24:48.660
We know you guys are
beefing with this group.

00:24:48.660 --> 00:24:49.720
Here are some job training.

00:24:49.720 --> 00:24:51.095
Here's some tattoo
removal if you

00:24:51.095 --> 00:24:52.849
want resources
and opportunities.

00:24:52.849 --> 00:24:54.890
But if that doesn't work,
here's a U.S. attorney.

00:24:54.890 --> 00:24:57.024
And surprisingly,
people take opportunity

00:24:57.024 --> 00:24:58.190
when it's presented to them.

00:24:58.190 --> 00:24:59.400
It's like, woah.

00:24:59.400 --> 00:25:00.650
KYLE EWING: Novel, novel idea.

00:25:00.650 --> 00:25:03.115
MICHAEL TUBBS: They don't
want to be gangsters.

00:25:03.115 --> 00:25:06.410
KYLE EWING: [CHUCKLES]
Hey how's it going?

00:25:06.410 --> 00:25:07.669
My name is Ally Bernstein.

00:25:07.669 --> 00:25:09.710
I'm on the Diversity
Markets team here at Google.

00:25:09.710 --> 00:25:13.750
And as one of the first people
that I met on my first day

00:25:13.750 --> 00:25:17.835
at Google, I wanted to say ,
I'm very proud of Michael Tubbs.

00:25:17.835 --> 00:25:19.160
You've come a long way.

00:25:19.160 --> 00:25:20.900
I've been crying this whole day.

00:25:20.900 --> 00:25:23.830
So thank you for
making me proud.

00:25:23.830 --> 00:25:27.219
I have a question
for you, actually.

00:25:27.219 --> 00:25:29.510
How have you thought about
ways to connect the problems

00:25:29.510 --> 00:25:30.760
that you're solving
here in Stockton

00:25:30.760 --> 00:25:32.560
to other cities that
are going through

00:25:32.560 --> 00:25:33.739
the same exact problems?

00:25:33.739 --> 00:25:35.280
Because I think it's
really important

00:25:35.280 --> 00:25:37.260
that some of the lessons
that you're learning

00:25:37.260 --> 00:25:39.420
are lessons that can
directly, immediately

00:25:39.420 --> 00:25:42.230
be applied to areas such
as Oakland, Long Beach,

00:25:42.230 --> 00:25:44.615
California, where I'm from,
and other major cities that

00:25:44.615 --> 00:25:45.790
are having some of
these same issues.

00:25:45.790 --> 00:25:48.220
So I wanted to get your
thoughts on what you guys were

00:25:48.220 --> 00:25:50.790
doing to spread that knowledge.

00:25:50.790 --> 00:25:53.430
MICHAEL TUBBS: I think
there's a couple things.

00:25:53.430 --> 00:25:57.200
I'm kind of cautious because
one year or two years is cool.

00:25:57.200 --> 00:25:59.410
But you need four or
five years to really

00:25:59.410 --> 00:26:01.090
be like, this is working.

00:26:01.090 --> 00:26:04.389
But generally-- I was just on a
panel with the mayor of Oakland

00:26:04.389 --> 00:26:05.680
and I told her about Ceasefire.

00:26:05.680 --> 00:26:08.230
We need to institutionalize
Ceasefire, do it right.

00:26:08.230 --> 00:26:11.370
I was just at a conference
with the mayor of Compton, Aja

00:26:11.370 --> 00:26:14.720
Brown, this amazing,
32-year-old, USC-trained

00:26:14.720 --> 00:26:16.410
planner who is now
the mayor of Compton.

00:26:16.410 --> 00:26:18.420
And I was telling her about some
stuff we're doing in Stockton.

00:26:18.420 --> 00:26:20.664
And then there's a lot of
networks and conferences

00:26:20.664 --> 00:26:22.830
and things that people are
so interested in Stockton

00:26:22.830 --> 00:26:25.050
because of a lot of
challenges we face.

00:26:25.050 --> 00:26:27.140
And we're kind of ground
zero for a lot of things,

00:26:27.140 --> 00:26:29.650
whether it's municipal
bankruptcy, or water issues,

00:26:29.650 --> 00:26:32.520
or homelessness, or we're
the foreclosure capital

00:26:32.520 --> 00:26:33.950
of the world, or homicide.

00:26:33.950 --> 00:26:35.810
We're really ground
zero for every problem

00:26:35.810 --> 00:26:37.292
facing the country.

00:26:37.292 --> 00:26:38.750
But it also gives
us an opportunity

00:26:38.750 --> 00:26:40.767
to emerge as one of
the leaders in terms

00:26:40.767 --> 00:26:42.100
of how you solve those problems.

00:26:42.100 --> 00:26:43.970
So we've been doing a good job.

00:26:43.970 --> 00:26:46.150
But I think once we have
some real concrete wins,

00:26:46.150 --> 00:26:49.710
we'll do a better job of telling
our story and helping to scale.

00:26:49.710 --> 00:26:50.820
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:26:50.820 --> 00:26:51.060
MICHAEL TUBBS: Go ahead.

00:26:51.060 --> 00:26:51.480
KETAKI SHRIRAM: Sorry, go ahead.

00:26:51.480 --> 00:26:52.320
MICHAEL TUBBS: No.

00:26:52.320 --> 00:26:53.580
KETAKI SHRIRAM: Go ahead.

00:26:53.580 --> 00:26:55.960
I was just going to say
with regards to the film,

00:26:55.960 --> 00:26:57.540
we sort of have similar thought.

00:26:57.540 --> 00:26:59.910
So we were really hoping to
screen the films in schools,

00:26:59.910 --> 00:27:01.993
and churches, and prisons
in different communities

00:27:01.993 --> 00:27:03.590
to try and really
get youth inspired

00:27:03.590 --> 00:27:05.696
to take political
action or to even

00:27:05.696 --> 00:27:06.820
aspire to higher education.

00:27:06.820 --> 00:27:09.860
And when we were in New York we
screened the film at a prison

00:27:09.860 --> 00:27:10.452
in Manhattan.

00:27:10.452 --> 00:27:12.160
And I think for all
of us that was really

00:27:12.160 --> 00:27:13.510
one of the most
moving experiences,

00:27:13.510 --> 00:27:15.051
was seeing how people
responded to it

00:27:15.051 --> 00:27:17.430
and how they were inspired
to make a difference.

00:27:17.430 --> 00:27:19.750
So on the film end, that's
what we're thinking.

00:27:19.750 --> 00:27:20.500
MICHAEL TUBBS: I'm
just going to say

00:27:20.500 --> 00:27:21.958
that's a big reason
why I wanted it

00:27:21.958 --> 00:27:24.457
and that's my big pitch
to people in terms of,

00:27:24.457 --> 00:27:26.790
if you help Stockton, you're
really helping the country.

00:27:26.790 --> 00:27:28.740
Because the problems
are concentrated here.

00:27:28.740 --> 00:27:30.115
And you're not
going to find them

00:27:30.115 --> 00:27:33.180
