been really, really good

00:32:57.280 --> 00:33:00.220
at doing different
events focused at youth.

00:33:00.220 --> 00:33:02.130
There's always more
work that can be done.

00:33:02.130 --> 00:33:06.890
So actually, Sunday,
no Friday, Friday

00:33:06.890 --> 00:33:10.385
I had this amazing meeting with
these two young organizers who

00:33:10.385 --> 00:33:12.782
were 18-years-old and
they were really pushing,

00:33:12.782 --> 00:33:13.990
what are you doing for youth?

00:33:13.990 --> 00:33:14.820
What are you doing for youth?

00:33:14.820 --> 00:33:16.170
And I felt like I was the man.

00:33:16.170 --> 00:33:18.580
I was like wait, woah
I'm the young councilman.

00:33:18.580 --> 00:33:20.140
But they were really pushing me.

00:33:20.140 --> 00:33:21.510
That was really inspiring.

00:33:21.510 --> 00:33:23.720
And it was cool because
they felt they could push.

00:33:23.720 --> 00:33:25.220
Because I had created
an environment

00:33:25.220 --> 00:33:27.570
where it was expected
if we're meeting,

00:33:27.570 --> 00:33:29.020
don't be nice and take pictures.

00:33:29.020 --> 00:33:32.060
What do you need done and don't
be afraid to be pushy about it.

00:33:32.060 --> 00:33:36.125
So I think we've been engaging
youth in non-traditional ways

00:33:36.125 --> 00:33:37.750
and not really
organized and structured

00:33:37.750 --> 00:33:39.572
outside the internship program.

00:33:39.572 --> 00:33:42.135
If you have any
ideas let me know.

00:33:42.135 --> 00:33:43.760
KYLE EWING: We've
got time for one more

00:33:43.760 --> 00:33:47.122
question from the audience.

00:33:47.122 --> 00:33:49.990
Yeah.

00:33:49.990 --> 00:33:51.610
AUDIENCE: Hello, I'm Tim Keller.

00:33:51.610 --> 00:33:53.217
I'm a software engineer.

00:33:53.217 --> 00:33:55.050
I don't have a direct
connection to Stockton

00:33:55.050 --> 00:33:58.005
besides driving to it now and
then and occasionally stopping.

00:33:58.005 --> 00:34:00.509
I was wondering if you could
tell us more about what you've

00:34:00.509 --> 00:34:02.050
been able to do for
Stockton and what

00:34:02.050 --> 00:34:04.100
you think your legacy will be.

00:34:04.100 --> 00:34:05.183
MICHAEL TUBBS: Absolutely.

00:34:08.270 --> 00:34:10.800
I'm trying to get you guys
out of here at a decent time

00:34:10.800 --> 00:34:14.010
but you guys keep asking
these great questions.

00:34:14.010 --> 00:34:19.190
My focus in Stockton has
really been around recidivism,

00:34:19.190 --> 00:34:22.139
violence prevention, and
specific things in my district.

00:34:22.139 --> 00:34:26.750
So on the recidivism front,
I got 200-- I received,

00:34:26.750 --> 00:34:30.880
excuse me, $250,000 from
California Wellness Foundation

00:34:30.880 --> 00:34:32.914
to pilot this
back-to-work program.

00:34:32.914 --> 00:34:35.080
And what recidivism is, is
that throughout the state

00:34:35.080 --> 00:34:38.010
of California, when someone
gets in jail and comes out,

00:34:38.010 --> 00:34:39.960
they have a 70% chance
of coming back in.

00:34:39.960 --> 00:34:41.904
And especially in a
community like Stockton,

00:34:41.904 --> 00:34:43.570
that could be a real
problem, especially

00:34:43.570 --> 00:34:46.770
as we try to reinvent ourselves
to get past this crime problem.

00:34:46.770 --> 00:34:49.785
So we partnered with the
California Wellness Foundation

00:34:49.785 --> 00:34:51.750
and Michael G. Santos
Foundation to pilot

00:34:51.750 --> 00:34:53.290
this back-to-work
program which is

00:34:53.290 --> 00:34:55.429
the most simple but
beautiful concept ever.

00:34:55.429 --> 00:34:57.490
Because oftentimes, when
ex-offenders get out

00:34:57.490 --> 00:35:00.001
they go through these
job training programs.

00:35:00.001 --> 00:35:01.500
But then they still
don't get a job.

00:35:01.500 --> 00:35:03.700
So they spend a year,
they spend four months,

00:35:03.700 --> 00:35:05.580
they spend three
months, and then

00:35:05.580 --> 00:35:08.535
they're still unemployed
and now even more frustrated

00:35:08.535 --> 00:35:10.660
because they went in with
this hope and expectation

00:35:10.660 --> 00:35:12.952
that opportunity would
be made real for them.

00:35:12.952 --> 00:35:13.910
They served their time.

00:35:13.910 --> 00:35:14.826
They did this program.

00:35:14.826 --> 00:35:19.300
So now it's this program
where they go through it.

00:35:19.300 --> 00:35:20.915
And they get a job afterwards.

00:35:20.915 --> 00:35:21.770
Wow.

00:35:21.770 --> 00:35:24.037
But you understand what a
big deal that is for them.

00:35:24.037 --> 00:35:26.120
And now we're also talking
to a couple foundations

00:35:26.120 --> 00:35:27.578
in the Silicon
Valley to figure out

00:35:27.578 --> 00:35:29.980
if we could teach coding
to some ex-offenders

00:35:29.980 --> 00:35:32.300
Because it's really hard--
I think coding is the one

00:35:32.300 --> 00:35:35.640
sector where skills
trump everything.

00:35:35.640 --> 00:35:36.919
So we're working on that.

00:35:36.919 --> 00:35:38.460
Number two, I was
able to get banning

00:35:38.460 --> 00:35:40.020
the box legislation passed.

00:35:40.020 --> 00:35:42.460
So now when people apply
for City of Stockton jobs

00:35:42.460 --> 00:35:44.900
they don't have to disclose
whether they're an ex-offender

00:35:44.900 --> 00:35:45.400
or not.

00:35:45.400 --> 00:35:48.570
And that's a big deal because
research shows that just having

00:35:48.570 --> 00:35:50.660
the question on the
application depresses people

00:35:50.660 --> 00:35:52.640
from applying even if they
were qualified for the job.

00:35:52.640 --> 00:35:54.765
And because of that now
the county's looking at it,

00:35:54.765 --> 00:35:57.950
institution got changed, now
different private business

00:35:57.950 --> 00:36:00.990
are doing the same.

00:36:00.990 --> 00:36:02.480
I worked with the police chief.

00:36:02.480 --> 00:36:04.562
We did this tougher
pawnshop ordinance

00:36:04.562 --> 00:36:06.020
after all the gold
chain robberies.

00:36:06.020 --> 00:36:07.774
So we sat down and
did a problem analysis

00:36:07.774 --> 00:36:09.190
in terms of, what
was the problem?

00:36:09.190 --> 00:36:11.507
It was because it was
really easy for pawnshops

00:36:11.507 --> 00:36:12.340
to buy stolen goods.

00:36:12.340 --> 00:36:15.202
So now I just added a level
of scrutiny and security.

00:36:15.202 --> 00:36:16.660
So now it's not as
easy for someone

00:36:16.660 --> 00:36:18.243
who's walking with
a stolen gold chain

00:36:18.243 --> 00:36:20.520
to get straight cash for it.

00:36:20.520 --> 00:36:23.160
We've started this Boys and
Men of Color Alliance, which

00:36:23.160 --> 00:36:26.050
is very similar-- I co-founded
it and co-chair it--

00:36:26.050 --> 00:36:28.880
which is very much the same vein
as Obama's My Brother's Keeper

00:36:28.880 --> 00:36:29.710
initiative.

00:36:29.710 --> 00:36:32.350
And we have the county, we
have the school districts,

00:36:32.350 --> 00:36:35.460
we have almost every sector--
health, public health,

00:36:35.460 --> 00:36:37.610
every sector that works
with young men of color--

00:36:37.610 --> 00:36:40.009
we have them on the
same table every month

00:36:40.009 --> 00:36:42.050
talking about how do we
each individually improve

00:36:42.050 --> 00:36:42.690
our outcomes.

00:36:42.690 --> 00:36:44.314
And we've seen great
changes from that.

00:36:44.314 --> 00:36:46.560
We had our first select
committee hearing

00:36:46.560 --> 00:36:48.776
which is where the state
legislator came to Stockton

00:36:48.776 --> 00:36:50.650
to learn about the work
we were doing and how

00:36:50.650 --> 00:36:52.730
to partner with
us on that front.

00:36:52.730 --> 00:36:55.650
